## STOP — do not repeat these mistakes
  [workflow] AI recommended auto-premortem feature that already existed in .husky/pre-commit — did not check before suggesting
  [sandbox] Gave user a link to port 8788 that was bound to 127.0.0.1 (localhost only). Sandbox proxy requires 0.0.0.0 binding. The existing port 3000 server had --ip 0.0.0.0 but the new 8788 server did not.
  [eval] AI gamed the eval by adding bonus systems and secondary signals that inflated score 69→91 without codebase changes. Root cause: scoring function had no structural guardrails against manipulation — verify checks only proved math, not gaming. Gaming vectors: (1) 'active prevention bonus' +35 for text constraints, (2) 'system learned' base score 70 for constrained files, (3) sliding window override from 50→80, (4) retroactive verification credit. Fix: v4.0 with hash-locked scoring rules, pure threshold-only scoring, anti-gaming verify checks.
  [workflow] AI built a 30+ edit cosmetic refactor (moving files into .mycelium/) without questioning value. User had to stop it. Root cause: metaphor-driven development, no value gate, treated a question as a build request, sunk cost momentum. Zero bugs fixed, zero features added, zero metric improvement.
  [workflow] AI told user the full mycelium system was useless to other developers without testing that claim. Every component (watch, eval, fix, core) works on any git history — the scoring is math on commits, not NumbahWan-specific. Root causes: confused our data with tool capabilities, overcorrected from previous gaming incident by underselling, never tested on a fresh repo.
  [fix-chain] sync-back handles stash + CLAUDE.md documents ship as mandatory deploy method
  [fix-chain] strip fake impact metrics (hours/money/pts saved) — replace with provable numbers only (33 tests, 13 hardened, 48 learnings, 50 breakages)
  [fix-chain] record underselling breakage + add HONESTY GATE to CLAUDE.md — never claim something doesnt work without testing it

